<Base
  title="About"
  description="About The Well — mission, governance, and what is in the repository."
>
  <h1 class="text-3xl mb-6">About</h1>
  <p class="mb-4">
    The Well is a free-to-read database of how federal and California state
    judges run their courtrooms — standing orders, filing preferences, motion
    practice cadence, and oral argument tendencies. The data is maintained by
    verified California-barred attorneys who contribute observations
    anonymously.
  </p>
  <p class="mb-4">
    The information is already public. Standing orders are on court websites.
    Local rules are free. But finding, reading, and cross-referencing those
    documents for 150 judges takes a week of work nobody has time to do. The
    Well changes that.
  </p>
  <h2 class="text-xl mt-8 mb-3">Licenses</h2>
  <ul class="mb-4 list-disc pl-6">
    <li><strong>Code:</strong> AGPL-3.0.</li>
    <li><strong>Data &amp; schema:</strong> CC-BY-SA 4.0.</li>
  </ul>
  <h2 class="text-xl mt-8 mb-3">Operator</h2>
  <p class="mb-4">
    The Well is maintained by Zack Pearson and the open-source community. It is
    operated by The Well Legal Inc., a Delaware C-corporation.
  </p>
</Base>
